 chosen for their long-standing interest in the intellectual evolution of their fields. They describe the origins and histories of US-based Area Studies programs, highlighting their complex, generative, and sometimes contentious relationships with the social science and humanities disciplines and their diverse contributions to the regions of the world with which they are concerned.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEducation. 4aGeneral. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aBonnell, Victoria E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowen, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreslauer, George W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComisso, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDirks, Nicholas B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrake, Paul W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutierrez, Brad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHilbink, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Pearl T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzanton, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSzanton, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTansman, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalder, Andrew G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024536540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093211140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932111423